	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=11&mid=96845345228003>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=11&mid=96845345228003>RE: Root vs. Snare</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=11&mid=96845345228003#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Sep 8th 6:50 PM 2000</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1412><span id= >Sarian</span></a><br><span id=notbold>3 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Root definitely has its failings, and as I'm only level 20 I can't comment on Snare.&nbsp;&nbsp;But there are ways to get around the problem with root breaking too early in the fight, namely by not opening with it as you describe.<br><br>In scenarios where root is unlikely to hold for long, I've had good success by opening with a bolt spell, from maximum range.  The fact that the bolt takes a while to hit the mob means that by the time the mob charges I'm ready to cast again (or nearly so).  I then follow with Tishan's Clash, stunning the mob and doing a little damage.  At that point I root, then hit it with Force Shock.  Even if the root breaks immediately, I've done potenitally about 324 damage to the mob before it even gets to me.  If the root holds, it's all gravy from there.<br><br>Of course this technique only works in flat, open spaces like the Karanas.  I've also used it to good effect in Orc Alley in Oasis.  Even if you're under 20 and don't have Tishan's yet, it can still be quite useful.  The point is to do as much damage as possible before the first root even has a chance to break.<br></p>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
